Milestone 1: Groups, Data, Website, and Extraction, Transformation, and Load

Introduction

In this project the general question I want to solve over all would be, within Palm Beach County Florida, are the public parks here accessible, in the sense that, are they accessible to bus stops, residential areas, train stations, etc. I would also like to figure out exactly where in Palm Beach County has the most accessible public parks and which has the least accessible ones. I have already hypothesized that areas near downtown West Palm Beach may have the most accessible parks due to the high concentration of public transport, however, given how I have lived in the area for some time, the parks are still a quite a distance away from the actual area. I would also think that areas more out towards Lake Okeechobee would be less accessible to considering, from what Ive seen, how semi-rural and sparsely populated it is.

The first piece of data I would utilize would be the basic location data of the parks in Palm Beach County sourced from the Florida Geospatial Open Data Portal. This will give me the name of the park, the address, the county (to which I would just filter on Palm Beach), the type of Park, whether it has a pool or as well as longitude and latitude. The question would be simple, what are the exact locations of these parks? This dataset would also help me figure out how many public parks we have in our county as well.

The second part of this project would be how we would gauge accessibility and we would need a couple of data sources for this. With open data coming from Palm Beach TPA, we will be able to derive the location of all Amtrak and Tri-Rail Stations in Palm Beach County, using the Palm Beach County Open Data Page, we could also extract the bus stops that are in the area, with this we would be able to look at the amount of bus stops that are nearest to each park. The question I would ask using these datasets would be how many of these transit areas are located around these parks, and which location, say for example municipality (at a general level) or park has the most transit stops closest to them. I believe I will most likely measure this by counting the amount of transit areas that are less than a 2-mile radius, I could also just convert the distance between two longitude and latitude points to get the number of miles as well.

I will be working on this project by myself, allocating several hours a week to working on it and making progress, I will employ the use of git as version control to make sure that my progress is being saved correctly om GitHub.

Milestone 2: Additional Extraction, Transform, and Load (ETL) + Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), and Model Proposal

For my extra peice of data, I wanted to factor in Walkability score. Thw Walkability Score is a metric used to determin how far a given location is to nearby amenities. This score is calculated based on intersection denisity, reidential density, accessbility if amenities such as grocery, stores, restaurants, and of course, parks and recreational areas! I chose to incorporate walkability simply because I thought it would be an interesting criteria to add onto my analysis of whether ort not certain parks are more accessible, considering how diverse given areas and locations are across palm beach county, I could imagine that looking at the walkability scores of the general location of each of these parks could give me a nice set number that could partially determine the accesibility value of each of these parks. One of the sources of this score would be www.walkscore.com/ that has several tables showcasing scores of different areas and states as well as allowing for a user to input a given location and fing out how walkable that location is, in order to access the data of for Palm Beach accounty, I decided to scrap a table that showcased the walkability score of cities in Florida and averaged it!

Scrapping Walkability Score Data

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

# Step 1: Get the page content
url = "https://www.walkscore.com/FL/"
response = requests.get(url)

# Step 2: Parse the HTML content
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Step 3: Find the table
# You may need to inspect the page to find the correct table
table = soup.find('table')  # Adjust if there are multiple tables or if the structure differs

# Step 4: Extract the headers
headers = []
for th in table.find_all('th'):
    headers.append(th.text.strip())

# Step 5: Extract the rows
data = []
for tr in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
    row = []
    for td in tr.find_all('td'):
        row.append(td.text.strip())
    data.append(row)

# Step 6: Create a DataFrame
Palm_Beach_Parks = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=headers)

# Step 7: Display the DataFrame

Scraping the WalkScore Website for each Parks Walkability score

In[25]:
import re

def get_walk_score(address):
    try:
        # Format the address for the URL
        formatted_address = address.replace(' ', '-')
        url = f"https://www.walkscore.com/score/{formatted_address}"
        
        # Send a GET request to the URL
        response = requests.get(url)
        
        # Check if the request was successful
        if response.status_code == 200:
            soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
            
            # Locate the walk score image element
            score_img = soup.find('img', {'src': re.compile(r'/badge/walk/score/\d+\.svg')})
            if score_img:
                # Extract the score from the src attribute
                score_url = score_img['src']
                score = re.search(r'/badge/walk/score/(\d+)\.svg', score_url)
                if score:
                    return score.group(1)  # Return the score as a string
                else:
                    return None
            else:
                return None
        else:
            print(f"Failed to retrieve data for {address}, Status code: {response.status_code}")
            return None
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error fetching score for {address}: {e}")
        return None

# Add walk scores to the DataFrame
Palm_Beach_Parks['WalkScore'] = Palm_Beach_Parks['ADDRESS'].apply(get_walk_score)

import folium

# Set up a map centered around Palm Beach County
m = folium.Map(location=[26.7056, -80.0364], zoom_start=10)

# Add each park to the map with color based on walkability score
for _, row in Palm_Beach_Parks.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row['LAT_DD'], row['LONG_DD']],
        radius=5,
        color="green" if row['WalkScore'] >= 76 else "blue" if row['WalkScore'] >= 51 else "orange" if row['WalkScore'] >= 26 else "red",
        fill=True,
        fill_opacity=0.7,
        popup=f"{row['ADDRESS']}: {row['WalkScore']}"
    ).add_to(m)

# Save or display map
m.save("parks_walkability_map.html")
m
